FT  14 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Jamaican economy grows 3.8%
JAMAICA'S economy grew 3.8 per cent last year, lifted by expansion in
agriculture, mining and manufacturing, writes Canute James in Kingston.
Mr Percival Patterson, finance minister, said the growth was achieved
despite 'adverse external shocks'. The island's economy grew 4.6 per cent in
1989. He said the agriculture sector expanded by 11.8 per cent in 1990, with
mining up 17.6 per cent and manufacturing up 4.1 per cent.
The island's trading position improved; the Dollars 724m (Pounds 420)
merchandise trade deficit was Dollars 98m less than the year-earlier
shortfall. Imports grew 1.7 per cent and exports 14.2 per cent.
Mr Patterson said public debt was Dollars 4.15bn at the end of 1990, Dollars
114m less than a year earlier.
